Building buy/sell strategies based on top investors behaviour¶

1. Intoduction: The 13F filings¶

The SEC's 13F is a quarterly report required to be filed by institutional managers that manage at least 100$ million. It discloses their equity holdings and can provide insights into what the top managers are doing. It informs what was bought and sold in the past quarter and must be filed until the filings date, 45 days after the end of the quarter.

As there is a 45 delay between the end of the semester and the filings date, as well as a delay from when the transaction was made, the stock purchases may have been made 45 to 135 days prior to the reported date, making the information less reliable and making it impossible to benefit from any transaction made because of short-term events.

The objective of this analysis will be to explore if, by considering the actions of multiple funds (and trying to find which stocks they seem to agree on), it is possible to find stocks that are likely to perform better than the S&P in the period after the filings date.

2. Collecting the data:¶

A webscraper was built to extract both the information of the past transactions made by the managers, as well as the stock prices in key dates.

Top managers¶

The data regarding the top managers characteristics can be found in https://www.dataroma.com/m/managers.php. It informs:

  • Name of the fund
  • Amount of capital held by the fund
  • Number of stocks the fund has at the current moment
  • Top 10 holdings at the moment

Historical transactions by fund¶

In the same website, the historical transactions each fund made by quarter is also reported (Ex:https://www.dataroma.com/m/m_activity.php?m=AIM&typ=a):

  • Quarter of transaction
  • Stocks the fund moved in the quarter.
  • If the fund ended up with a net buy or net sell at the end of the semester.
  • How much change this sell/buy action corresponded to the overall portfolio in %.

Stock prices¶

For each stock in each quarter, the prices in key dates (start semester, end semester, start of filings date this semester, start of filings date next semester) were obtained using yahoo finance.

  • start_date: Date the semester started
  • end_date: Date the semester ended
  • start_filings: Filings date of the semester (45 days after end_date)
  • end_filings: Filings date of the next semester (45 days after next semester's end date)

Each date has a corresponding stock price and SPY (S&P500) price.

For each transaction, a variable "alpha_1sem+45" is obtained: It is the return between the start_filings and end_filings date the stock had above the SPY.

As an example, suppose AAPL was one of the stocks most bought in 2021Q1:

Start date: 01/01/2021

End date:31/03/2021

Start filings: 16/05/2021 (Price: 127.45$ - Price SPY: 415.52$)

End filings: 16/08/2021 (Price: 151.12$ - Price SPY: 446.97$)

Inc_1sem+45 (AAPL)=(151.12-127.45)/127.45=18.6%

Inc_1sem+45_spy =(446.97-415.2)/415.52=7.6%

Alpha_1sem+45=18.6%-7.65% = 11%

By looking into what the investors did in the first 3 months of the year and investing in the stock from may to august, it was possible to obtain a gain 11% higher than the gain of the S&P in the same period.

The table below shows a sample of 20 buy/sell actions with the information mentioned above.

def read_data_excel():
    data= pd.read_excel('summary_buy_sells_v2.xlsx', index_col=0)
    data['year']=data['Quarter'].apply(lambda x:int(x.split(' ')[0]))
    for col in ['start_price','end_price','start_filings_price','end_filings_price']:
        data=data[data[col]>0.01]
    data=data.dropna(subset=['start_price','end_price','start_filings_price','end_filings_price'],axis=0)
    data['Inc_1sem']=(data['end_price']-data['start_price'])/data['start_price']
    data['Inc_1sem+45']=(data['end_filings_price']-data['start_filings_price'])/data['start_filings_price']
    data['Inc_1y+45']=(data['end_filings_1y_price']-data['start_filings_price'])/data['start_filings_price']

    data['Inc_1sem_spy']=(data['end_price_spy']-data['start_price_spy'])/data['start_price_spy']
    data['Inc_1sem+45_spy']=(data['end_filings_price_spy']-data['start_filings_price_spy'])/data['start_filings_price_spy']
    data['Inc_1y+45_spy']=(data['end_filings_1y_price_spy']-data['start_filings_price_spy'])/data['start_filings_price_spy']

    data['alpha_1sem']=data['Inc_1sem']-data['Inc_1sem_spy']
    data['alpha_1sem+45']=data['Inc_1sem+45']-data['Inc_1sem+45_spy']
    data['alpha_1y']=data['Inc_1y+45']-data['Inc_1y+45_spy']
    return data

3. Defining the objective, hypothesis and methodology¶

Before processing and filtering the data, it is important to have a well defined objective, set of hypothesis and idea of how the algorithm will work.

3.1 Objective¶

The objective of the analysis will be to build a set of rules based on investor and transaction information that can indicate which funds are likely perform above the S&P and which funds are likely to perform below the S&P.

The strategies will be based on the group of investors, rather than any particular fund. They will be based on the net number of funds that bought the stock (number that bought - number that sold), as well as how much change there was (Transactions with higher % change to portfolio are likely to be more important).

3.2 Hypothesis and simplifications¶

Simplifications

  • Dividends will not be considered.

Hypothesis

  • There is a high enough number of funds to base the analysis on (the data extracted from the site included only 72 funds, but there are many more that fill 13F's and did not appear).
  • It is also assumed there was no biased criteria the site used to choose the 72 investors presented in the webpage.
  • Transactions with a higher "% change to portfolio" are likely to be more important.
  • Managers that hold a lower number of stocks are likely to be more precise in their choice. A transaction made in a fund with 600 stocks is likely to be less important than a transaction made by a fund that has 10 stocks, for example.
  • Funds behaved in a similar way both in past and present (number of stocks in portfolio did not change a lot over the years)

3.3 Methodology¶

  1. Filters are applied to disconsider transactions judged unimportant (Ex: transactions that had a change in portfolio of less than 0.2%). The filters and subset of data considered are analyzed in the next section.
  2. Strategies are built around the following criteria:
  • Strategy 1: Buying funds with highest net buy/sells (Ex: buying a fund because it had a value of 6 net buy/sell: - 8 buys ans 2 sells)
  • Strategy 2: Buying funds with highest net % change to portfolio (Ex: buying a fund because it had a value of 8.5% net change: 1 fund increased 4%, other fund increased 5%, other fund decreased 0.5%)
  • Strategy 3: Buying funds with highest net buy/sell, taking into consideration past fund performances. Same as strategy 1, but best performing funds have a higher weight to their actions.
  1. Sensibility analysis: Study how modifications in the filters may modify the performance of the strategies.

4. Studying, processing and filtering the data¶

4.1 Choosing filters¶

4.1.1 Choosing the limit of stocks in a fund¶

The idea of this filter is to exclude funds that have too many held stocks, as they may be less imporant and decisive than funds that have very few held stocks.

On the other hand, it is not interesting to limit the maxmimum number of stocks held too low, as there won't be enough funds and data to base the strategies on.

The figure below shows that very few funds have more than 100 held stocks. It also shows that considering only funds with less than 20 stocks reduces the data size too much: Almost no transaction (unique stock+quarter combination) appeared more than 3 times.

For now, only funds with less than 100 stocks will be considered.

def plot_numb_transactions_as_function_of_variable(x_var,xlabel,title,x_limit):
    row_list=[]

    for stocks_in_port in sorted(list(pd.unique(data[x_var]))):
        if x_var=='stocks_in_port':
            var_df=data[data[x_var]<=stocks_in_port]
        else:
            var_df=data[data[x_var]>=stocks_in_port]
        unique_values=var_df.drop_duplicates(subset=['Quarter','Ticker'])
        higher_than_3_transactions=var_df.groupby(['Quarter','Ticker']).count()[['Action']].reset_index()
        higher_than_3_transactions=higher_than_3_transactions[higher_than_3_transactions['Action']>=3].count()['Action']
        row_list+=[[unique_values.shape[0],var_df.shape[0],stocks_in_port,higher_than_3_transactions]]

    df_change=pd.DataFrame(row_list,columns=['unique_values','total_values','x_var','more_than_3_transactions'])
    fig,ax1=plt.subplots(figsize=(12,8))
    ax2 = ax1.twinx()

    l1=ax1.plot(df_change['x_var'],df_change['unique_values'],label='Total unique transactions')
    l2=ax1.plot(df_change['x_var'],df_change['total_values'],label='Total transactions')
    l3=ax2.plot(df_change['x_var'],df_change['more_than_3_transactions'],label='Transactions made by at least 3 funds',
                c='green')
    lns=l1+l2+l3
    ax1.legend(lns,[l.get_label() for l in lns],loc=0)
    plt.xlim(x_limit)

    ax2.set_ylabel('Transactions made by at least 3 funds',color='green')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Total transactions/unique transactions',color='black')
    ax1.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    ax1.set_title(title)
    #ax1.set_xticks([0.2,0.5,1,2,3,4,5])
    ax1.grid(axis='x')
    if x_var=='stocks_in_port':
        ax1.invert_xaxis()
    if x_var=='% change to portfolio':
        ax1.set_xticks([0.2,0.5,1,2,3,4,5])
        ax1.set_ylim(0,30000)
        ax2.set_ylim(0,3000)

4.1.2 Choosing the minimum % change required¶

Some of the funds operations presented a very low "% change to portfolio", sometimes as low as 0.01%. These low transactions don't indicate a change in strategy of the fund regarding the stock (it could just be a small movimentation of the funds portfolio), and are only adding noise.

It is interesting to filter transactions with changes to portfolio too small. At the same time, if this filter value is too high, the filter may be too strong and not enough data is left to analyze.

The graph below shows that only limiting transactions to changes of at least 3% leaves us with less than 150 transactions (unique combinations of stock+quarter) made by at least 3 investors. For this initial analysis, the chosen limit will be 1%.

4.1.3 Capping the % change to portfolio.¶

The second strategy will use the sum of the "net % change", trusting that funds that made a higher investment (Ex: 5% of portfolio into BABA) are much more confident in the stock than funds that made a lower investment (Ex: 0.35% of portfolio into BABA).

The problem arises however when a fund makes a bet that represents a very large amount of their portfolio, thus making it the sole decider on the investment (Ex: in one quarter, suppose a fund increased the position in BABA to 30% of portfolio, while 10 other funds increased the position into AAPL by 2.5%. The method would choose BABA, solely because it has the highest sum value).

To avoid this problem on basing the strategy on one big bet, the % change to portfolio is capped at a certain value. For this current analysis the value used will be 5%. However the sensibility regarding this value will be studied on a later section.

def data_filter_and_process(data_in,filter_percent_port,max_number_of_stocks_in_port,perc_increase_cap):
    data_out=data_in[(data_in['% change to portfolio']>filter_percent_port)&(data_in['stocks_in_port']<max_number_of_stocks_in_port)]

    data_out['% change to portfolio']=data_out['% change to portfolio'].apply(lambda x:min(x,perc_increase_cap))
    return data_out
data_filt=data_filter_and_process(data,filter_percent_port,max_number_of_stocks_in_port,perc_increase_cap)

4.2 Investor analysis¶

In this section, it will be analyzed if funds that performed well in the past are likely to perform well in the future.

The characteristics of the funds will also be studied to see if there is anything that can indicate a better performance.

4.2.1 Correlation of past performance and future performance.¶

To test wheter funds that overperformed in the past are likely to overperform in the future we will consider the alpha of each transaction.

For each fund, the median alpha before 2018 and after 2018 was calculated. Only funds that had both more than 20 transactions in both periods were considered, to make sure the values are more representative of the performance of the fund. The figure below shows a regression between alpha before 2018 and alpha after 2018. Although statistically significant (p_value<0.05), the very big variance in the alpha shows this relation is very weak.

def plot_confidence_interval(df,x_var,y_var,xlabel,ylabel,title,correction):
    df=df.sort_values(by=x_var)
    x=df[[x_var]]-correction
    y=df[y_var]-correction
    model=sm.OLS (y,x).fit()
    st, data, ss2 = summary_table(model, alpha=0.05)

    fittedvalues = data[:, 2]
    predict_mean_ci_low, predict_mean_ci_upp = data[:, 4:6].T
    predict_ci_low, predict_ci_upp = data[:, 6:8].T
    slope=model.params[0]
    p_value=pd.read_html(model.summary().tables[1].as_html(),header=0,index_col=0)[0]['P>|t|'][0]
    r2=pd.read_html(model.summary().tables[0].as_html(),index_col=0)[0][3][0]
    corr=pearsonr(df[x_var],df[y_var])[0]
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    plt.scatter(df[x_var]*100,df[y_var]*100)
    #plt.plot([-7.5,7.5],[-7.5,7.5],'k--')
    plt.plot([0+correction*100,0+correction*100],[(min(y)+correction)*100*1.02,(max(y)+correction)*100*1.02],'k--')
    plt.plot([(min(x.values)[0]+correction)*100*1.02,(max(x.values)[0]+correction)*100*1.02],[0+correction*100,0+correction*100],'k--')
    plt.plot((x+correction)*100, (fittedvalues+correction)*100, 'g-', lw=2)

    plt.fill_between(((x.T.values+correction)*100)[0],(predict_mean_ci_low+correction)*100,(predict_mean_ci_upp+correction)*100,color='b',alpha=0.4,label='regression confidence interval')
    plt.fill_between(((x.T.values+correction)*100)[0],(predict_ci_low+correction)*100,(predict_ci_upp+correction)*100,color='#888888',alpha=0.1,label='distribution confidence interval')

    plt.xlim((min(x.values)[0]+correction)*100*1.02,(max(x.values)[0]+correction)*100*1.02)
    plt.ylim((min(y)+correction)*100*1.02,(max(y)+correction)*100*1.02)

    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.legend()
    bbox_args = dict(boxstyle="round", fc="0.8")
    text = plt.annotate('Slope= {:.2f}\n p_value={:.2e}\n RSquared={:.2f}\n Correlation={:.2f}'.format(slope,p_value,r2,corr),
                    xy=(((max(x.values)[0]+correction)*100*0.8, 0.2)), xycoords=("data", 'axes fraction'),
                    xytext=(0, -20), textcoords='offset points',
                    ha="center", va="top",
                    bbox=bbox_args)

    return model

4.3 Metrics analysis¶

After analyzing the individual buy/sell actions of each investor, the actions are grouped together into transactions (unique combination of stock and quarter). For each transaction, the number of different funds that bought/sold were counted. The net % change was also calculated, taking into account the "% change to portfolio" of each fund action.

Finally, a net investor score was also calculated. This uses information about the top performing funds in the period before 2018.

If a fund made lower than 20 transactions before 2018, then it has a weight of 2.5. If the fund made more than 20 transaction, it will receive a score based on the median alpha of its "buys". The top 25% funds will receive a weight of 4, the next 25% a weight of 3, the next a weight of 2, and the bottom 25% will receive a weight of 1.

So, if fund 1 (weight 2.5) and fund 2 (weight 1) bought, while fund 3 (weight 4) sold the stock. The net investor score would be: 2.5+1-4=-0.5

A summary of some of these unique transactions is shown in the table below.

def generate_df_transaction_metrics(data):
    dict_metrics={}

    for index, row in data.iterrows():
        if not row['Quarter'] in dict_metrics:
            dict_metrics[row['Quarter']]={}
        if not row['Ticker'] in dict_metrics[row['Quarter']]:
            if row['Action']=='Buy':
                # buys, sells, net buy/sells, net change, buyer list, seller list, return 1sem+45, return 1sem+45spy, return 1sem, return 1sem spy, return between end of sem and start of filings
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']]=[1,0,1,row['% change to portfolio'],[row['Investor']],[],row['Inc_1sem+45'],row['Inc_1sem+45_spy'],row['Inc_1sem'],row['Inc_1sem_spy'],(row['start_filings_price']-row['end_price'])/row['start_filings_price'],(row['start_filings_price_spy']-row['end_price_spy'])/row['end_price_spy'],row['Company'],investor_score[row['Investor']]]
            elif row['Action']=='Sell':
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']]=[0,1,-1,-row['% change to portfolio'],[],[row['Investor']],row['Inc_1sem+45'],row['Inc_1sem+45_spy'],row['Inc_1sem'],row['Inc_1sem_spy'],(row['start_filings_price']-row['end_price'])/row['start_filings_price'],(row['start_filings_price_spy']-row['end_price_spy'])/row['end_price_spy'],row['Company'],-investor_score[row['Investor']]]
        else:
            if row['Action']=='Buy':
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][0]+=1
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][2]+=1
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][3]+=row['% change to portfolio']
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][4]+=[row['Investor']]
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][-1]+=investor_score[row['Investor']]

            elif row['Action']=='Sell':
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][1]+=1
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][2]-=1
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][3]-=row['% change to portfolio']
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][5]+=[row['Investor']]
                dict_metrics[row['Quarter']][row['Ticker']][-1]-=investor_score[row['Investor']]

    df_transactions=pd.DataFrame.from_dict({'{} / {}'.format(i,j): dict_metrics[i][j] 
                            for i in dict_metrics.keys() 
                            for j in dict_metrics[i].keys()},
                        orient='index',columns=['Buys','Sells','Net Buy/Sells','Net % change','Buyers','Sellers','Inc_1sem+45','Inc_1sem+45_spy','Inc_1sem','Inc_1sem_spy','Inc_between_semester_end_start_filings','Inc_between_semester_end_start_filings_spy','Company','Net investor score']).reset_index()
    df_transactions['Quarter']=df_transactions['index'].apply(lambda x:x.split(' / ')[0])
    df_transactions['Ticker']=df_transactions['index'].apply(lambda x:x.split(' / ')[1])
    df_transactions=df_transactions.drop('index',axis=1)
    df_transactions['Alpha_1sem']=df_transactions['Inc_1sem']-df_transactions['Inc_1sem_spy']
    df_transactions['Alpha_1sem+45']=df_transactions['Inc_1sem+45']-df_transactions['Inc_1sem+45_spy']
    df_transactions['Alpha_between_semester_end_start_fillings']=df_transactions['Inc_between_semester_end_start_filings']-df_transactions['Inc_between_semester_end_start_filings_spy']
    df_transactions['Net % change bins']=pd.cut(df_transactions['Net % change'],np.linspace(-10,10,20))
    df_transactions['Net investor score bins']=pd.cut(df_transactions['Net investor score'],np.linspace(-10,10,20))
    df_transactions['Net Buy/Sells bins']=pd.cut(df_transactions['Net Buy/Sells'],[-100,-2.5,-1.5,-0.5,0.5,1.5,2.5,100],labels=['-3 or less','-2','-1','0','1','2','3 or more'])
    df_transactions['Alpha_1sem bins']=pd.qcut(df_transactions['Alpha_1sem'],10)
    df_transactions['Alpha_between_semester_end_start_fillings bins']=pd.qcut(df_transactions['Alpha_between_semester_end_start_fillings'],10)
    return df_transactions

4.4 Effect of realized returns on the returns after the filings date.¶

Another effect to explore was whether the return after the filings date would be lower if the stock price already increased in:

  • between the end of the semester and the filings date.

5. Simulating strategies¶

Each of the three proposed metrics was simulated using the following methodology:

  1. Start at the defined semester.
  2. In the semester, buy the top 4 stocks according to the selected metric (each stock representing 25% of the total porfolio).
  3. In a similar way, buy the lowest 4 stocks according to the metric. This will be called the "inverse method".
  4. Simulate the gains in the semester of each of the 4 stocks and take the average. This is the return of the semester following the strategy.
  5. Repeat for the next semester, buying the top 4 stocks of the semester. Repeat until the final semester.

5.1 Method 1: Net Buy/Sells¶

By simulating the method for the entire period (2013-2021), the method managed to perform better than the S&P. On the other hand, the reverse method also managed to underperform the S&P.

The scatterplot shows that the method, most of times, performed above the S&P, but there were some quarters it did underperform. The method was also much more noisier than the S&P: It managed to have both the highest and lowest return.

        series_spy+=[series_spy[-1]*(1+inc_spy[i])]
        series_method_p+=[series_method_p[-1]*(1+inc_method_p[i])]
        series_method_n+=[series_method_n[-1]*(1+inc_method_n[i])]
        series_random+=[series_random[-1]*(1+inc_method_rand[i])]
    comp_growth_spy=(series_spy[-1]**(1/len(series_spy))-1)*100
    comp_growth_p=(series_method_p[-1]**(1/len(series_method_p))-1)*100
    comp_growth_n=(series_method_n[-1]**(1/len(series_method_n))-1)*100
    comp_growth_rand=(series_random[-1]**(1/len(series_random))-1)*100

    if plot_return_over_time:
        plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
        plt.plot(year_dates,series_spy[1:],label='SPY -> compound growth:{:.2f}%'.format(comp_growth_spy))
        plt.plot(year_dates,series_method_p[1:],label='Method (Top {}) -> compound growth:{:.2f}%'.format(number_of_selections,comp_growth_p))
        plt.plot(year_dates,series_method_n[1:],label='Method (Bottom {}) -> compound growth:{:.2f}%'.format(number_of_selections,comp_growth_n))
        plt.legend()
        plt.title('Method {} - Buying based on {}'.format(method,metric[0]))
        plt.xlabel('Date')
        plt.ylabel('Increase since {} Q1'.format(period_range[0]))


    p_value_p=ttest_rel(inc_method_p,inc_spy)[1]
    p_value_n=ttest_rel(inc_method_n,inc_spy)[1]
    p_value_p_n=ttest_rel(inc_method_n,inc_method_p)[1]


    if print_p_values:
        print('Performing a paired t-test (two samples are related) for method {}. P-values:\n Method vs SPY: {:.2e}\n Inverse Method vs SPY: {:.2e}\n Inverse Method vs Method: {:.2e}'.format(method,p_value_p,p_value_n,p_value_p_n))
    if plot_scatter_graph_period:
        df_gains=pd.DataFrame(vector_gains_p,columns=['Quarter','Spy','Method'])

        fig,ax=plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(10,10))
        df1=df
        ax.scatter(y=df_gains['Quarter'], x=df_gains['Method'], s=75, color='red', alpha=1,zorder=2,label='Return method',marker='o')
        ax.scatter(y=df_gains['Quarter'], x=df_gains['Spy'], s=75, color='blue', alpha=1,zorder=2,label='Return SPY',marker='^')
        ax.legend(loc=2)
        for i, p1, p2 in zip(df_gains['Quarter'], df_gains['Method'], df_gains['Spy']):
            if p1>p2:color='green'
            else:color='red'
            newline([p1, i], [p2, i],ax,color)
        plt.xlabel('Return in Quarter (%)')
        plt.ylabel('Quarter')
        plt.title('Return of method when compared to SPY return QoQ')

        df_gains=pd.DataFrame(vector_gains_n,columns=['Quarter','Spy','Method'])

        fig,ax=plt.subplots(1,1,figsize=(10,10))
        df1=df
        ax.scatter(y=df_gains['Quarter'], x=df_gains['Method'], s=75, color='red', alpha=1,zorder=2,label='Return method',marker='o')
        ax.scatter(y=df_gains['Quarter'], x=df_gains['Spy'], s=75, color='blue', alpha=1,zorder=2,label='Return SPY',marker='^')
        ax.legend(loc=2)
        for i, p1, p2 in zip(df_gains['Quarter'], df_gains['Method'], df_gains['Spy']):
            if p1>p2:color='green'
            else:color='red'
            newline([p1, i], [p2, i],ax,color)
        plt.xlabel('Return in Quarter (%)')
        plt.ylabel('Quarter')
        plt.title('Return of inverse method {} when compared to SPY return QoQ'.format(method))
    return comp_growth_spy,comp_growth_p,comp_growth_n,comp_growth_rand,bought_by_quarter_method,sold_by_quarter_method

6. Sensitivity analysis¶

6.1 Method 1: Net Buy/Sells¶

Now that the methodology has been defined, it is interesting to understand how the returns of the method could change based on the parameters used during the analysis. The main parameters for method 1 were:

  1. Minimum % of portfolio change: The method only considered transactions that changed the portfolio by more than 1%, how would the result change when considering other values?
  2. Maximum stocks in fund portfolio: The method only considered funds that had less than 100 stocks in their current portfolio. How would the result change when changing this value to include more/less funds?
  3. Top stocks to select: The method selected the top 4 performing stocks by semester, what would happen if more/less stocks were selected in each semester?

To understand how the performance changes with parameters, a sensibility analysis will be performed. Using each combination of variables, the compound growth will be calculated and compared with the growth of the SPY in the same period. The sensibility analysis will also use a random selection of stocks to compare the method results.

The analysis will be separated in two periods: 2013-2017 and 2018-2021. This is done so that some considerations/analysis can be made based upon the 2013-2017 period analysis. These conclusions are then applied to the 2018-2021 to see if they hold.

The following combinations will be considered:

  1. Minimum % of portfolio change (0.5%, 1%, 1.5%, 2%)
  2. Maximum stocks in fund portfolio (50,100,1000)
  3. Top stocks to select (2,3,4,5,6,8)

The results for the first method are shown below:

def plot_sensitibity_compound_growth(minimum_percent_list,max_stocks,top_to_select_list,perc_increase_cap_list,metric,starting_date,ending_date):

    data= read_data_excel()

    data_sensitivity=[]

    if metric[0]=='Net Buy/Sells':
        product_comb=itertools.product(minimum_percent_list,max_stocks,top_to_select_list)
    elif metric[0]=='Net % change':
        product_comb=itertools.product(perc_increase_cap_list,max_stocks,top_to_select_list)
    


    for iterative1,iterative2,iterative3 in product_comb:
        if metric[0]=='Net Buy/Sells':
            filter_percent_port=iterative1
            perc_increase_cap=perc_increase_cap_list[0]
        elif metric[0]=='Net % change':
            perc_increase_cap=iterative1
            filter_percent_port=minimum_percent_list[0]
        max_number_of_stocks_in_port=iterative2
        top_to_select=iterative3

        #t0=time.time()
        data_filt=data_filter_and_process(data,filter_percent_port,max_number_of_stocks_in_port,perc_increase_cap)
        data_filt[(data_filt['year']>=starting_date)&(data_filt['year']<ending_date)]
        #print(0,(time.time()-t0))
        #t0=time.time()

        df_transactions=generate_df_transaction_metrics(data_filt)
        #print(1,(time.time()-t0))
        #t0=time.time()
        comp_growth_spy,comp_growth_p,comp_growth_n,comp_growth_rand,_,_=simulate_compound_growth(df_transactions,[starting_date,ending_date],metric,0,top_to_select,0,0)
        #print(2,(time.time()-t0))
        #t0=time.time()

        data_sensitivity+=[[perc_increase_cap,filter_percent_port,max_number_of_stocks_in_port,top_to_select,comp_growth_p,comp_growth_n,comp_growth_rand]]

    df_sensibility=pd.DataFrame(data_sensitivity,columns=['perc_inc_cap','filter_percent','filter_n_stocks','numb_selections','method','method_n','method_random'])

    for filter_n_stocks_sel in max_stocks:
        fig=plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
        outer_grid = gridspec.GridSpec(1,3, wspace=0.1, hspace=0)
        for i in np.arange(3):
            if i==0:
                method='method'
            elif i==1:
                method='method_n'
            else:
                method='method_random'
            df_sensibility_filt=df_sensibility[df_sensibility['filter_n_stocks']==filter_n_stocks_sel]
            mean_total=np.mean(df_sensibility_filt[method])
            std_dev_tot=np.std(df_sensibility_filt[method])

            mean_by_percent=df_sensibility_filt.groupby(['filter_percent']).mean()[[method]]
            std_by_percent=df_sensibility_filt.groupby(['filter_percent']).std()[[method]]

            mean_by_n_sel=df_sensibility_filt.groupby(['numb_selections']).mean()[[method]]
            std_by_n_sel=df_sensibility_filt.groupby(['numb_selections']).std()[[method]]
            if metric[0]=='Net Buy/Sells':
                df_pivot=df_sensibility_filt.pivot(index='numb_selections',columns='filter_percent',values=method)
                mean_by_percent=df_sensibility_filt.groupby(['filter_percent']).mean()[[method]]
                std_by_percent=df_sensibility_filt.groupby(['filter_percent']).std()[[method]]
            elif metric[0]=='Net % change':
                df_pivot=df_sensibility_filt.pivot(index='numb_selections',columns='perc_inc_cap',values=method)
                mean_by_percent=df_sensibility_filt.groupby(['perc_inc_cap']).mean()[[method]]
                std_by_percent=df_sensibility_filt.groupby(['perc_inc_cap']).std()[[method]]
            gspec= gridspec.GridSpecFromSubplotSpec(40,40, subplot_spec=outer_grid[i])
            ax = plt.Subplot(fig, outer_grid[i])
            fig.suptitle('Choosing only funds with less than {} stocks in portfolio         Obs: Compound growth SPY (QoQ):{:.1f}%         Period:{}-{}'.format(filter_n_stocks_sel,comp_growth_spy,starting_date,ending_date-1))
            left_top_ax=plt.subplot(gspec[:27,:27])

            sns.heatmap(pd.DataFrame([mean_total,std_dev_tot],index=['Mean','Std.Dev']),annot=True,fmt='.1f',ax=bottom_right_ax,linecolor='black',cbar=False,vmin=-10**8,vmax=10**8,cmap='bwr',linewidth=1)

            bottom_right_ax.set_title('Overall')

            for ax in [left_top_ax,left_middle_ax,bottom_right_ax]:

6.2 Method 2: Net % change¶

Similary to method 1, the most important parameters will be iterated and tested.

  1. Maximum % of portfolio change cap: The transactions made by a fund will be capped at an upper percentage. This is done so that if a fund decided to invest 50% of its portfolio into one stock, the method considers only an upper limit. During the previous analysis, this upper limit was equal to 5%.
  2. Maximum stocks in fund portfolio: The method only considered funds that had less than 100 stocks in their current portfolio. How would the result change when changing this value to include more/less funds?
  3. Top stocks to select: The method selected the top 4 performing stocks by semester, what would happen if more/less stocks were selected in each semester?

The following combinations will be considered:

  1. Maximum % of portfolio change cap (2, 3, 5, 10%)
  2. Maximum stocks in fund portfolio (50,100,1000)
  3. Top stocks to select (2,3,4,5,6,8)
  4. Minimum % of portfolio change: As this only affects the second method very little, it will not be iterated. A constant value equal to 0.2% is considered.

As such, depending solely on this analysis could be risky, as oscillations were very high and returns not very reliable. The analysis, however, is useful to point the investor to potential good investments (or bad investments when using the reverse method) and can be used as a screening tool, showing the top recommendations of the model which could be further analyzed using other criteria.

def get_stocks_sold_bought_method(minimum_percent,max_stocks,top_to_select,perc_increase_cap,metric,starting_date,ending_date):

    return comp_growth_spy,comp_growth_p,comp_growth_n,bought_by_quarter_method,sold_by_quarter_method

8. Final comments¶

By analyzing the top investors behavior the following conclusions can be made:

  1. Basing the strategy on one transaction did not give a very high alpha.
  2. Instead, by choosing stocks that a lot of funds were flocking to, it was possible to find stocks likely to overperform the SPY.
  3. The inverse method was much more reliable in choosing stocks that would underperform the SPY than the method was in choosing stocks that would overperform the SPY.
  4. Method 1 was much less likely to change behavior when parameters were changed when compared to method 2.
  5. Although both methods seemed to perform better than the SPY, the very high oscillations verified in the analysis makes the methods riskier and subject to short term underperformance.
  6. The strategies are useful as a screening tool, helping separate potential stocks.
  7. The analysis was based on the assumption that there was no bias by the website "DATAROMA" in selecting the 72 funds available in the site. If the website chose to show only funds that performed well in the past, then the analysis and results may not hold.
